Spring and autumn are unpredictable and can range from cool to warm, although they are usually mild with low humidity. Summers are typically hot and humid, with a daily mean temperature of 77.5&#160;°F (25.3&#160;°C) in July.<sup id="cite_ref-NOAA_txt_166-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NOAA_txt-166">&#91;164&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Nighttime temperatures are often enhanced due to the <a href="/wiki/Urban_heat_island" title="Urban heat island">urban heat island</a> effect. Daytime temperatures exceed 90&#160;°F (32&#160;°C) on average of 17 days each summer and in some years exceed 100&#160;°F (38&#160;°C), although this is a rare achievement, last occurring on July 18, 2012.<sup id="cite_ref-New_York_City_Weatherbox_NOAA_168-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-New_York_City_Weatherbox_NOAA-168">&#91;166&#93;</a></sup> Similarly, readings of 0&#160;°F (−18&#160;°C) are extremely rare, last occurring on February 14, 2016.<sup id="cite_ref-169" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-169">&#91;167&#93;</a></sup> Extreme temperatures have ranged from 106&#160;°F (41&#160;°C), recorded on July 9, 1936, down to −15&#160;°F (−26&#160;°C) on February 9, 1934;<sup id="cite_ref-NOAA_txt_166-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NOAA_txt-166">&#91;164&#93;</a></sup> the coldest recorded wind chill was −37&#160;°F (−38&#160;°C) on the same day as the all-time record low.<sup id="cite_ref-170" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-170">&#91;168&#93;</a></sup> The record cold daily maximum was 2&#160;°F (−17&#160;°C) on December 30, 1917, while, conversely, the record warm daily minimum was 87&#160;°F (31&#160;°C), on July 2, 1903.<sup id="cite_ref-New_York_City_Weatherbox_NOAA_168-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-New_York_City_Weatherbox_NOAA-168">&#91;166&#93;</a></sup> The average water temperature of the nearby Atlantic Ocean ranges from 39.7&#160;°F (4.3&#160;°C) in February to 74.1&#160;°F (23.4&#160;°C) in August.<sup id="cite_ref-171" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-171">&#91;169&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The city receives 49.5 inches (1,260&#160;mm) of precipitation annually, which is relatively evenly spread throughout the year. Average winter snowfall between 1991 and 2020 was 29.8 inches (76&#160;cm); this varies considerably between years. <a href="/wiki/Hurricane" class="mw-redirect" title="Hurricane">Hurricanes</a> and <a href="/wiki/Tropical_storm" class="mw-redirect" title="Tropical storm">tropical storms</a> are rare in the New York area.<sup id="cite_ref-172" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-172">&#91;170&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Hurricane_Sandy" title="Hurricane Sandy">Hurricane Sandy</a> brought a destructive <a href="/wiki/Storm_surge" title="Storm surge">storm surge</a> to New York City on the evening of October 29, 2012, flooding numerous streets, tunnels, and subway lines in Lower Manhattan and other areas of the city and cutting off electricity in many parts of the city and its suburbs.<sup id="cite_ref-173" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-173">&#91;171&#93;

